ndie, Frankrig","Torre, Devonshire, England":"Torquay, Devon, England","Torre Brewer Manor, Tormohun, Devon, England":"Tormohun, Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1086–1115":"1086–1115","1090–1121":"1090–1121","1114–1205":"1114–1205","1106":"1106","1205":"1205","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1114":"1114","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Torre, Devonshire, England":"Torquay, Devon, England","Torre Brewer Manor, Tormohun, Devon, England":"Tormohun, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1086–1115":"1086–1115","1090–1121":"1090–1121","1114–1205":"1114–1205","1106":"1106","1205":"1205","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1114":"1114","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Torre, Devonshire, England":"Torquay, Devon, England","Torre Brewer Manor, Tormohun, Devon, England":"Tormohun, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Briwere","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Pierre, Adrien, Aurele, Benedicte, Benoit, Colette, Fernand, Gaston, Marcel, Micheline.","French (<b>Brière</b>): topographic name from a regional variant of Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heather’ (see   Bruyere  ), or a habitational name from La Brière, the name of several places mainly in the northern part of France, from the same word.","History: Jean Brière from Clarbec in Calvados, France, married Jeanne Grandin in Quebec City, QC, in 1671."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruyere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Fernand, Jacques, Marcel.","French (<b>Bruyère</b>): from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heather’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived in a place where heather grew, or a habitational name from one of the places in France (for example in Calvados) named with this word. Compare   Labruyere  .","Altered form (<b>Bruyère</b>) of French <b>Bruguier</b>: habitational name from (Le) Bruguier, the name of several places in the southeastern part of France, a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":0,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":10,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":20,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William de Briwere I was born in 1086, in Normandy, France. He had at least 1 son with Mrs William de Briwere Heiress of Torre Brewer. He died in 1115, in Torquay, Devon, England, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1086–1115":"1086–1115","1090–1121":"1090–1121","1114–1205":"1114–1205","1106":"1106","1205":"1205","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1114":"1114","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Torre, Devonshire, England":"Torquay, Devon, England","Torre Brewer Manor, Tormohun, Devon, England":"Tormohun, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1086–1115":"1086–1115","1090–1121":"1090–1121","1114–1205":"1114–1205","1106":"1106","1205":"1205","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1114":"1114","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Torre, Devonshire, England":"Torquay, Devon, England","Torre Brewer Manor, Tormohun, Devon, England":"Tormohun, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1086–1115":"1086–1115","1090–1121":"1090–1121","1114–1205":"1114–1205","1106":"1106","1205":"1205","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1114":"1114","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Normandie, France":"Normandie, France","Torre, Devonshire, England":"Torquay, Devon, Angleterre","Torre Brewer Manor